.TH Q3N 1 "2026-06-30" "1.1.5" "Q3N Manual"

.SH NAME
q3n \- Quote Triple-Slash Notation CLI — manage quoted text collections

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B q3n
.I command
.RI [ options ] " [" args ]
.br
.B q3n
\-\-help
.br
.B q3n
\-\-version
.br
.B q3n help
.br
.B q3n tutorial

.SH DESCRIPTION
Q3N (Quote Triple-Slash Notation) is a plain-text file format for storing
quotations, citations, and annotated excerpts with their source URIs.
Entries are delimited by \fB///\fR (open) and \fB\\\\\fR (close).

A Q3N entry looks like this in its source form:

.RS
.nf
/// https://example.com/article /// cite/article:
Quoted text goes here.
It can span multiple paragraphs.
\\\\\
.RE

.PP
.B q3n
is the command-line tool for creating, viewing, searching, and managing
Q3N files.

.SH COMMANDS

.SS show
Display entries from a Q3N file.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n show <file> [n] [--json]
.RE

With an optional entry number, shows only that entry along with its
raw Q3N source. With \fB--json\fR, outputs structured JSON.

.SS list (ls)
Scan a directory and list all entries found across Q3N files.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n list [directory] [--json]
.RE

.SS create
Interactive wizard for creating a new Q3N entry.
Walks through source-type selection, URI entry, tagging, and quote text.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n create <file>
.RE

If the file exists, the new entry is appended. Otherwise a new file is
created.

.SS edit
Edit an existing entry interactively. Prompts for URI, tag, and quote
text, showing the current values as defaults.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n edit <file> [n]
.RE

Without an entry number, lists all entries and prompts for selection.

.SS search
Search entry text using a regular expression pattern.
Matches are shown with surrounding context and highlighted.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n search <pattern> [file-or-directory]
.RE

.SS stats
Show collection statistics: entry count, character/word counts,
tag distribution (with bar chart), and domain distribution.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n stats [file-or-directory] [--json]
.RE

.SS export
Export entries to an alternative format.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n export <file> -o <output> -f <format>
.RE

Supported formats: \fBtxt\fR (plain text), \fBjson\fR (structured data),
\fBmd\fR (Markdown with blockquotes), \fBhtml\fR (self-contained HTML),
\fBindex\fR (Markdown index table), \fBfortune\fR (fortune cookie format),
\fBanki\fR (Anki-compatible CSV), \fBq3n\fR (canonical Q3N).

.SS import
Import entries from another file (Q3N or JSON) into a Q3N file.
If the destination is a directory, a new file is created.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n import <source> <destination> [-f q3n|json]
.RE

.SS index
Generate a markdown index of all entries showing a table with
entry numbers, URIs, tags, and previews, grouped by tag.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n index [file-or-directory]
.RE

.SS init
Create a new empty Q3N file with the \fB#!q3n-format\fR header.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n init <file>
.RE

.SS fortune
Display a random quote from a Q3N file or directory as an ASCII art fortune cookie.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n fortune [file_or_dir] [-c N] [--art TYPE] [--no-art] [--filter-tag TAG] [--filter-scheme SCHEME]
.RE

.SS validate
Validate all URIs in a Q3N file. Prints OK or an error per entry; exits with code 1 if any URIs are invalid.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n validate <file>
.RE

.SS cite
Format entries as citations in a chosen style.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n cite <file> [--style mla|apa|chicago|bibtex] [--entry N] [--all]
.RE

.TP
.B --style
Citation style: \fBmla\fR (MLA 9, default: apa), \fBapa\fR (APA 7), \fBchicago\fR (Chicago 17), \fBbibtex\fR (BibTeX).
.TP
.B --entry N
Format only the Nth entry (1-based).
.TP
.B --all
Format all entries.

.SS run
Run a plugin's standalone function with an optional Q3N file.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n run <plugin> [file] [plugin-args...]
.RE

Available built-in plugins: \fBfortune\fR, \fBcite\fR, \fBanki\fR.

.SS config
Show, edit, or install user configuration files.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n config [--show] [--edit] [--install] [--force]
.RE

.TP
.B (no flags)
Print the config file path and whether it exists, plus the active stylesheet.
.TP
.B --show
Print all effective settings (defaults merged with the user file).
.TP
.B --edit
Open \fBq3n.conf\fR in \fB$EDITOR\fR (or \fBnano\fR if unset). Creates the file first if it doesn't exist.
.TP
.B --install
Copy the example \fBq3n.conf\fR and \fBstyle.qss\fR to \fB~/.config/q3n/\fR. Skips existing files.
.TP
.B --force
Overwrite existing files when used with \fB--install\fR.

.SS tutorial
Display an interactive tutorial introducing the Q3N format and CLI commands.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n tutorial
.RE

.SS help
Show this man page or detailed help for any command.

.B Usage:
.RS
q3n help [command]
.RE

.SH FILE FORMAT

.B Q3N
uses the following structure:

.RS
.nf
#!q3n-format

/// <source_uri> [/// <tag>:]
<quoted text, possibly multi-line>
\\\\\
.RE

.TP
.B #!q3n-format
Optional header for file-type identification.
.TP
.B /// <uri> [/// <tag>:]
Opening delimiter, source URI, and optional tag. The URI is any valid
scheme-prefixed identifier (https://, file://, isbn://, doi://, etc.).
Tags use a slash for hierarchy (e.g., \fBcite/article\fR, \fBnote/idea\fR)
and are terminated by a colon.
.TP
.B <quoted text>
The content — any UTF-8 text, multiple lines.
.TP
.B \\\\
Closing delimiter (three backslashes) on its own line.

.SS URI Schemes

.TP
.B https:// http://
Web page URLs.
.TP
.B file://
Local file paths; append \fB#line=N\fR for line references.
.TP
.B isbn://
Book references; format: \fBisbn://ISBN;'Title';'Author';Year\fR.
.TP
.B doi://
Academic paper DOIs.
.TP
.B arxiv://
arXiv preprint IDs.
.TP
.B yt://
YouTube video identifiers (\fByoutube://\fR is accepted as an alias).
.TP
.B pubmed://
PubMed article IDs (PMID).
.TP
.B orcid://
Researcher ORCID iDs; format: \fBorcid://0000-0002-1825-0097\fR.
.TP
.B spotify://
Spotify content; format: \fBspotify://track:ID\fR or \fBspotify://album:ID\fR.
.TP
.B osm://
OpenStreetMap features; format: \fBosm://node|way|relation/<id>\fR.
.TP
.B geo:
Geographic coordinates (RFC 5870, colon-only — no //); format: \fBgeo:<lat>,<lon>[?z=<zoom>]\fR.
.TP
.B overpass://
Overpass API queries; format: \fBoverpass://<query>\fR.
.TP
.B wikipedia://
Wikipedia articles; format: \fBwikipedia://Article_Title\fR or \fBwikipedia://lang/Article_Title\fR (lang is a 2-letter ISO code, default en).
.TP
.B github://
GitHub repositories and resources; format: \fBgithub://owner/repo\fR or \fBgithub://owner/repo/issues/123\fR.
.TP
.B q3n://
Person references; format: \fBq3n://@handle;email;'Name'\fR.

.SH EXAMPLES

Create your first Q3N collection:
.RS
$ q3n init my-quotes.q3n
$ q3n create my-quotes.q3n
.RE

List entries and show one in detail:
.RS
$ q3n list .
$ q3n show my-quotes.q3n 1
.RE

Export as Markdown:
.RS
$ q3n export my-quotes.q3n -o quotes.md -f md
.RE

Search across all files:
.RS
$ q3n search "Stonewall" .
.RE

Validate all URIs:
.RS
$ q3n validate my-quotes.q3n
.RE

Format a citation:
.RS
$ q3n cite my-quotes.q3n --style bibtex --entry 1
.RE

Display a random fortune:
.RS
$ q3n fortune my-quotes.q3n
.RE

.SH ENVIRONMENT

No environment variables are required. The tool auto-detects color
support based on whether stdout is a terminal. Pass \fB--no-color\fR
to disable ANSI escape sequences.

.SH FILES

Q3N files conventionally use the extension \fB.q3n\fR.
Alternative extensions: \fB.q3nt\fR, \fB.quotation\fR, \fB.quotes\fR.

